  <abstract>A white advertising card for Joy’s Flowers, featuring a scary, fanciful image of a dragon-like creature drawn in black ink with long claws, huge wings, a long neck, and covered in scales. A poem appears below the monster, indicating that the creature is a Jabberwock, who does not want toys for Christmas, but rather, wants Santa Claus to bring her flowers from Joy’s. Joy Floral Company was the oldest florist in Nashville, established in 1877 by Canadian immigrants Thomas C. Joy and his father, Thomas S. Joy. At the time of this ad, their main retail location was at 601 Church Street. Forms part of the Businesses Ephemera Subject Files. 1 advertising card ; b&amp;w ; 3 x 6 in.</abstract>
